Imagine a very long web page with many sections (for example, an HTML specification on one page). If the user requests a specific section (e.g., page.html#section7), how about if the web server streams that section first and then the other sections?
Stream order:
1. Begin of the HTML document until <body>
2. HTML for section 7
3. HTML for sections 1, 2, 3 etc.
Then the browser would ensure that sections 1 to 6 *over* section 7 are displayed on the webpage.
Does that make sense? Would it be helpful?
The linked section (#section7) should be rendered as quickly as possible without having to implement elements again with JavaScript. I just want a very long HTML document, but the linked sections should be rendered as quickly as possible. This should work with HTML.
The content could be streamed, and then the browser would insert all <contents> into the <div>.
<div id=sec1></div>
<div id=sec2></div>
etc.
<div id=sec7>section 7…</div>
<contents for=sec1>section 1…</contents>
<contents for=sec2>section 2…</contents>
usw.
It would not be streamed in order, but the browser would assemble the HTML document as if it had been streamed in order.
@user22 You can also reorder documents without using JS. You should not use the hash part of the URL if you want the server to do something, but you can use query string parameters so that the server knows which section you want first. When reordering the parts, you have several options:
1. Use CSS
2. Use a template with sections
@user23 Yes. The problem is that the visual order (what the user sees) does not match the DOM order. It would be useful to have an HTML function that allows content to be assembled in the DOM order even though it is not streamed in order.
But the idea with slots looks promising. I'll give it a try.
@user22 Oh, do you want the browser to bring the DOM order into correct sequence?
@user23 Yes, that's the idea. Section 7 would be streamed first so that the user can see it as soon as possible. If this could be done without affecting the DOM order, that would be good, then the browser would ensure that the resulting DOM order matches the visual order.
So section 7 should be streamed first, but the final result should look as if all sections had been streamed in order.
@user22 @user23 Check out PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
